  "prompt": "How much of demonetized money, might not come back to the banking system?",
  "response": "The amount of demonetized money that might not return to the banking system can vary depending on the specific details of the demonetization process and the country in question. Typically, demonetization involves the removal of certain currency notes from circulation, which are then replaced with new notes. \n\nIn India's demonetization event in November 2016, for example, the government demonetized \u20b9500 and \u20b91,000 notes. According to the Reserve Bank of India (RBI), approximately 99.3% of the demonetized currency had returned to the banking system by the end of the process. This suggests that a very small percentage\u2014less than 1%\u2014did not come back to the banking system.\n\nThe reasons for some money not returning could include unaccounted or illicit funds, money held by individuals who were unable or unwilling to exchange it within the stipulated timeframe, or logistical challenges in remote areas.\n\nTherefore, the percentage of demonetized money that does not return to the banking system would depend on factors such as the effectiveness of the demonetization process, public awareness and compliance, and the extent of informal or unaccounted economic activities in the country.",
